{
  "doc_id": "46512",
  "text": "Prolonged sitting is highly prevalent in modern society [CITATION_1] , and it is composed of numerous diverse behaviours many of which (eg, seated reading, writing, and screen viewing) but not all (seated cycling or rowing) contribute to the total time spent sedentary. There is some evidence that a secular trend of increasing sedentary time has coincided with continuing emergence of the obesity epidemic [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , leading to the conjecture that a causal relationship may exist. However, most aetiological investigations of sedentary time and obesity have measured TV-viewing duration only, which is an imperfect and unrepresentative proxy of the total time spent sedentary [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . More studies are needed to investigate the total sedentary time, also measured more precisely by objective instead of self-report methods, and its association with obesity in youth, particularly as doubts have arisen as to whether an association exists for total sedentary time that is independent of physical activity [CITATION_6] .",
